<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-319-715  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 319 715.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Feb 14 1989 v138 n47,781 pC1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ailing robot industry is turning to services.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Holusha, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The robotics industry, which has not done well over the last threeyears, might improve as it gets free of dependence on industrialapplications, moving instead into services.andP;  Joseph Engelberger,an industry pioneer, says: 'We see applications in fast food,hospitals, commercial cleaning and support for aged, infirmpeople.' Early in the decade, the robotics industry sold $550million of machines a year, but then it was discovered that robotsdo not simply replace factory workers: attempts to automate cancause as many problems as they solve.andP;  The industry faltered.andO;Less than $300 million of machines were sold in 1988.andO;Nevertheless, Engelberger and others are enthusiastic about amarket for service robots, foreseeing a market that will developmore quickly than it did for industrial machines.andP;  The slump, theysay, is a temporary reaction to overheated expectations.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Robotics IndustryIndustry AnalysisHome RobotsRobotic Industries AssociationGrowthOutlookIndustrial RobotsService IndustrySales.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphphotograph.andO;Caption:   The robotics industry slump. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>